rounds.response:
I’m working out my current portfolio value:

11 Wheat × 5  = 55  
21 Wood  × 10 = 210  
12 Sheep × 14 = 168  
16 Brick × 29 = 464  
13 Ore   × 38 = 494  
Total = 55 + 210 + 168 + 464 + 494 = 1,391.

Brick is the cheapest-in-value resource I have on a per-unit basis, and Ore is the most expensive-in-value per unit, so a deal that lets me turn surplus cheap resources into extra Ore keeps overall value climbing fastest. I can spare Brick because I have a big surplus (16), and I could also part with a moderate amount of Wood. At the same time, keeping at least one of every resource prevents locking myself out of future flexibility.

Here’s the opening proposal tailored to that thinking:

[Offer: 4 Brick, 6 Wood -> 4 Ore, 1 Brick]

This yields:

- I give away the lowest-value-per-unit items (Brick and Wood).  
- I gain valuable Ore.  
- I still keep 12 Brick and 15 Wood—ample future flexibility.  
- The projected net value gain for me is +58 (140 given out vs. 198 received).

rounds.response:
Let me quickly reassess what just happened.

Current inventory  
Wheat 11×5 = 55  
Wood 21×10 = 210  
Sheep 12×14 = 168  
Brick 16×29 = 464 (now just 12 left after the rejected offer)  
Ore 13×38 = 494  

Proposed last turn: I offered 4 Brick + 6 Wood for 4 Ore + 1 Brick.  
Net for me: gain 4 Ore (152 value) − lose 4 Brick (116 value) = +36 value.  
Player 0 rejected it.  Apparently they don’t want to lose Ore (highest-value commodity) or were offended by the requested return Brick.

Immediate take-away: trading Ore away from me is attractive to me, but hurt Player 0’s wallet (since they’d lose Ore value). I should focus on lower-impact tweaks for them.

Aim for “low-stakes, win-win”.  
What I’m short on: Basically everything trades at par except Ore & Brick. So I can still turn some Brick into Ore, just don’t ask for so much Ore all at once.  
Try a tighter ratio.

New offer  
Offer 2 Brick + 2 Wood → 1 Ore + 2 Brick  

Net for me:  
+1 Ore (+38) −2 Brick (–58) +2 Brick (+58) = gain 38 value (fractionally rising my Ore count while netting value).  
Player 0 only parts with 1 Ore and receives 2 Brick, an immediate +20 value for them (2*29 – 1*38 = 58–38 = +20).  
Trade looks fair to them this time, and still good for me.

[Turn 3]
